ANTHRAX - INDIA (02): (CHHATTISGARH), DEER IN ZOO, NOT
******************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

[1]
Date: Sat 1 Feb 2014
Source: The Times of India [edited]
http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/home/environment/wild-wacky/Chhattisgarhs-22-spotted-deer-didnt-die-due-to-anthrax-Report/articleshow/29727538.cms


A report from the Indian Veterinary Research Institute (IVRI) stated that the deaths of 22 spotted deer on 16 Jan 2014 at Kanan Pendari Zoo at Bilaspur were not due to anthrax; the report termed it as negative on Saturday [1 Feb 2014]. The official source said that, following the report, specialists from Wild Life of India and IVRI would visit Bilaspur's Nandan Kanan Pendari Zoo on 4 Feb 2014 for further investigation.

"The Forest Department's surveillance teams, which have been on a visit to nearby areas of the zoo within a radius of 10 km, didn't find a single sick animal whom they could vaccinate. Hence, it's clear that the virus [sic] was definitely not the reason for the animals' deaths," an official said.

Demanding a high level probe, the opposition Congress said that the Indian Veterinary Research Institute has rejected state wildlife officials' preliminary claim that the animals died due to anthrax infections. In a statement issued here, state Congress spokesman Shailesh Nitin Trivedi said the deaths of 21 spotted deer were the outcome of criminal negligence on the part of zoo officials, who tried to cover up the deaths by propagating that it could be due to anthrax infection.

Trivedi said the Congress in Bilaspur had also raised the question of how the animals died one by one within a short span of time, raising doubts about whether the spotted deer were poisoned. He said there was an urgent need to conduct an inquiry by an independent agency into the circumstances which led to the deaths of the zoo animals.

Opposition leaders in Bilaspur had alleged on 17 Jan 2014 that a local BJP legislator and his friends had "partied" at the zoo the night before 21 spotted deer were found dead. They alleged that the anthrax theory was floated deliberately in order to create a scare so as to divert attention from other circumstances that could have come to light during investigations.

Earlier, principal chief conservator of forests (PCCF) Ram Prakash had told reporters: "The spotted deer died due anthrax infection. An analysis of symptoms confirms that the animals were infected by bacteria called _Bacillus anthracis_. The dead herbivorous animals showed symptoms of anthrax bacteria as blood came out through the mouth and anus. The stomach swelled like a balloon because of infection," he had said.

[byline: Rashmi Drolia]

