******
[2]
Date: Sat 1 Feb 2014
Source: India TV Crime Desk [edited]
http://www.indiatvnews.com/crime/news/latest-news-bilaspur-zoo-cheetals-found-dead-5186.html


The mysterious deaths of 21 cheetals in Bilaspur zoo which occurred on the night of 14 Jan 2014 are being connected with the party which some BJP men held inside the zoo premises the same night.

Initially, anthrax was blamed for the deaths. However, wildlife experts and veterinary doctors have ruled out the possibility of the disease. Doctors and experts are not satisfied with the report provided by the state animal husbandry claiming anthrax as the reason behind the deaths of 21 cheetals. The experts say that the disease cannot cause sudden death in such large numbers. Also, the presence of disease was not found inside the zoo premises.

The cheetals were seen healthy at 8 pm that night but were found dead the next morning by the guard.

Local residents reported that the party took place inside the zoo and how BJP man Shankar Mali and his son Neeraj Mali took control over the zoo. The locals alleged that the party organized inside the zoo could not have taken place without the father-son duo's permission. Neeraj Mali himself confirmed that a party took place in the zoo. However, he denied his involvement and presence in the zoo that night.

Meanwhile, the principal chief conservator of forests, Ramprakash has denied that there was a party inside the prohibited area of Bilaspur zoo that night.

The team of doctors along with the zoo doctor and veterinarian filed a report in which they claimed anthrax to be cause of the deaths. No post mortem was conducted on dead cheetals. The burial of cheetals in haste without performing the [necropsies] is what made the wildlife experts suspect the involvement of outsiders.

The veterinary department crosschecked the reports and found that there were no signs of disease in the zoo. The other 33 cheetals in the zoo were found perfectly healthy. In the case of anthrax being spread in the area, the remaining cheetals would have also shown some sign of the disease. It was also found that the cheetals had vertical slits on their bodies, which could have been caused with a sharp object.

A probe into the case is being demanded by Bilaspur Congress leaders, as they suspect a human role behind the deaths of the cheetals.

